title: For Sale/Trade:  Winchester Model 1897 Trench Gun
postcontent:
This gun was given to me by my father, who got it from his uncle. He was an officer in the Richmond PD, and this was apparently his issued weapon. Serial number puts it at 1917, which makes it a WW1 ear shotgun. It has the flaming bomb and "US" ordnance markings.
After doing lots of research on these guns, there was a batch of surplus 97s that didn't make it overseas, and they sent to the Va National Guard and later sold to the Richmond PD. 
There is wear around the action and pump from use, and slight pitting along the barrel and tube. The heat shield, for whatever reason, has been removed. The stock is original as is the finish. It functions well, and it's been out trap shooting a few times.

title: For Sale:  ODI custom Viking Combat 1911
postcontent:
Rare custom 1911 in great condition. I have been looking for one of these for two years, you don't see them often in Alaska.
 Omega Defense Industries in New Jersey made only 1400 of these 1911's in 1981 and 1982. They are factory versions of the Seecamp custom Double Action/Single Action commander sized 1911, based on the Colt commander 1911. They were one of the early all stainless steel 1911's, and also one of the first double actions, and actually worked better than most of the other double actions that came out in the 80's. 
This gun was obviously worked on as the slide has no markings, and only the serial number is on the frame, and I beleive an Essex Arms kit was used, which would make it even more valuable as the quality is increased as less cast parts are used. It could also have been upgraded with Caspian or Seecamp parts, and only 300 of the Seecampt kits were made after ODI went under. The butt grip safety is disabled...most people disabled all safeties on these guns as there were issues with them. Tru Dot trijicon sights have been added, as well as buffalo bone grips. If you want to keep it classic, then order some teak wood grips so it will look original. This is a collectors piece that would compliment a collection, but can also be used as a daily carry. I will be firing it this weekend and will give an update.

I am looking for cash, but would consider a nice 1911 or stainless 10 mm plus cash. 
Must be 21 with a state ID and willing to sign a bill of sale.

located rearward, far away from the fouling and debris of the breech face. Since the block is visible, the user may ascertain its proper operation at any time. Even if the pistol falls and strikes the ground muzzle down, the firing pin will not strike the primer.
4. 3-Dot Sight System: Features a white ‘3-dot’ sight pattern for quick acquisition of the target. The rear sight is designed to provide a front projection so that, in
an emergency, the user may retract the slide single-handedly by pushing the rear sight against the edge of a table, door, etc.
5. Ambidextrous Safety (Type F): The ambidextrous safety lever, easily accessible by the thumb or a right or left handed shooter, is spring loaded so it’s either positively “on” or “off”. The safety lever also functions as the pistol’s decocking lever. When pushed down, the rear part of the firing pin (striker) is rotated out of alignment with the front part of the firing pin. (NOTE: Type C does not have an external safety/decocking lever). Additional hammer drop catch (half cock notch) prevents striking of the firing pin unit in the remote chance of unintentional hammer drop.
6. External Hammer Design: A traditional feature of Beretta pistols, this design provides the most energy to the firing pin, virtually eliminating the possibility of
misfires due to light primer strikes. Also provides an immediate visual and tactile indicator as to the cocked/uncocked status of the pistol.
7. Individual Size Grips: Pistol may be configured with small, medium or large backstraps to individually fit the hand of each shooter. The backstraps are checkered to ensure a firm grip in both wet or dry shooting conditions. Three backstraps included with every pistol.
8. Reversible Magazine Release: Multiple-sized, reversible magazine release buttons allow for customization to the individual’s hand size. Small size comes standard on the gun, while medium and large buttons are available as accessories and easy replacement. Each size may be positioned for right-handed or left-handed use.

9. Simple Field Stripping: Pistol is designed for extremely quick and simple field stripping. Disassembly latch does not remove from the gun, preventing accidental
dropping and loss. Reassembly is easy and accidental misassembly of parts is prevented by the distinctive design.
10. Light Technopolymer Frame: The light, yet durable, frame employs modern thermoplastic technology through the use of Corrosion resistant fiberglass reinforced polymer.
11. Barrrel: The Px4’s unique rotating barrel and locking system dissipates recoil energy radially, reducing felt recoil and muzzle rise. This is the strongest Beretta pistol action. Chrome lined barrels provide extreme corrosion resistance, as well as ease of cleaning. Barrels also feature a deeply recessed combat muzzle crown to protect the rifling.

title: For Sale:  CZ P-06 - Incorrect/Scam listing alert!
postcontent:
This listing: http://www.armslist.com/posts/2262513/ohio-handguns-for-sale--cz-75-p-06-with-tru-dot-night-sights-must-sell-today--------  is BS.  There is NO SUCH THING as a CZ P-06 with a stainless steel frame, or a stainless steel slide.  This gun has most likely had the finish removed and just has the bare metal polished.  Untreated carbon steel such as this WILL RUST.  I've contacted CZ-USA and they have verified that they have never made/sold any stainless version of the P-06.  The other issue is that the seller claims to have installed $100 set of night sights.  The CZ P-06 comes from the factory with night sights, so this statement is totally incorrect.  

I have contacted this seller to explain to him the incorrectness of his statements and he doesn't seem to care, so it's clearly deliberate.  This guy is the kind of person who ruins armslist for everybody.

title: Want To Buy:  Want to buy/refurb/repair used gun safes and antique safes.
postcontent:
I am a certified Safe and Vault technician and I am interested in any tired, old, scratched, dented, locked out, fed up safes. I will look at any safe made of metal, even the older ones like mosler, diebold (heavy, decorative and often have huge wheels on the bottom) and other antiques. Here is a few gun safes I know I would be interested in: Liberty, canon/Remington, browning, Winchester, American security(amsec). Just send me a photo or a good description with some dimensions and I will let you know if I am interested.

Not interested in sentry safe or any of the cheaper big box store units (unless you are locked out, I could open it for you for trade). I opened and repaired a Canon gun safe recently in exchange for a S&W 442 w/some great accessories, probably worth 500-600 total. Something like a liberty gun safe puts up a bigger fight so we would haggle it up a bit but you get the idea. I would encourage comparative estimates so we all know we are getting a good deal. I try my best to not drill, I have an auto dialer to try if you think you know some of the numbers or if you aren't in a huge hurry (it can take a day or two), I have a lot of fancy tricks for the electronic locks to avoid drilling, I have many factory contacts for support and an outstanding drill rig if it comes to that. I repair my holes with carbide bit tips and ball bearings so if we do drill it would be the last time that spot gets drilled (holes & repairs are always concealed under the dial/keypad/lock face).

I would provide identification, resume, references and you provide a fair trade and something for me to do. This is something I am doing on the side as a hobby to keep my trade skills sharp. I am willing to drive out further than any of the locksmiths will too, its the best way to get me out seeing new parts of OR. 

I have included a couple photos of myself on miscellaneous jobs.
1. opening a bank vault (sometimes its cheaper to just go through the wall)
2. opening a National Guard armory vault, installing security cameras, opening an Air Force classified documents file cabinet safe (startled by boss for photo), and auditing a roll cage install
3. my auto-dialer looking shiney on a safe

I take security very seriously and if you seem even the slightest bit shady I will wish you well on your way. I will ask appropriate questions before I spend any time driving. I will need to see and verify proof of ownership before I work on any safe. As far as purchasing your used safe I am open to many 'conditions' of safe but I wont be interested in crusty rustys that have been left out in the elements.

+Want to buy safes (for cash)
+Want to repair/service/maintain safes (for trade)
